RESEARCH SUBJECT CONSENT FORM 



Title: Concept Induction Using Large Language Models 



Investigator: Pascal Hitzler 

Daytime Phone Number: 785-532-6350 



Purpose: You are invited to participate in a research study on assessing how well people can understand and use the explanations an Artificial Intelligence (AI) system provides for its reasoning process in an image categorization task. This study is funded by Hitzler Startup Kansas State University. You must be 18 years old or older and be an English speaker to participate in this research study. 



Procedure: You will be shown images that belong to different categories, as well as explanations that were generated about why those images were placed into categories. You will then be asked to judge which images the categorization explanations best match. You will also be asked to provide additional ratings and feedback about the explanations that you see. Finally, we will ask you some general questions about your thoughts, feelings, and behaviors. These tasks are expected to take approximately 40 minutes to complete. 



Voluntary Participation and Freedom to Withdraw: You understand that your participation is voluntary and, should you decide not to participate, there will be no penalty or loss of benefits to which you would otherwise be entitled. There is no alternative procedure for this study except to not participate. If you decide to withdraw there will be no penalty or loss of benefits to which you would otherwise be entitled. 



Privacy and Confidentiality: You understand that your identity will remain undisclosed in any report of this research. Raw data will be available to members of the research team, who will treat it as confidential. In order to process payments, we will collect your MTurk ID. After payments are processed, we will remove this information from the data. This anonymous data will be made available via online repositories for other researchers to use. 



Potential Benefits and Risks: There are no known risks associated with your participation in this study other than the risk of a breach in confidentiality and loss of anonymity. Successful completion of this study will potentially provide benefits to society and the scientific community. For example, a better understanding of how well people can understand the reasoning of AI systems may have important public policy implications, as well as provide insight into how AI reasoning can be made more understandable so that people can better rely on AI systems. 



Costs and Remuneration: You will incur no costs as a result of participating in this study other than your personal time and internet access. You will receive compensation for participation in this study according to the rate specified on the Mechanical Turk HIT listing that advertised this research study. Compensation will be provided through Amazon Mechanical Turk at the rate specified in the listing (estimated at $7.50/hour). You will be paid for a completed survey but not for an incomplete survey. 



Whom to Contact: If you have questions or concerns related to your rights, the research procedures, or research purpose, concerns about the research, complaints about the research, or you think you have been hurt by the research, you can contact the Investigator, Dr. Pascal Hitzler. Contact information is provided below. 

Dr. Pascal Hitzler, Principal Investigator, Kansas State University, 785-532-6350, hitzler@k-state.edu

Strategy Description: I looked at the overall objects in image A and compared them to image B. Then, I looked at each word to see if the words in each group fit in with Image A. It was necessary to look at every picture in A in order to determine the best group.
EasyHardTrials: The image with the bakeries and the shoe and purse shops seemed more difficult because neither group applied to all images.
Fatigue: No, in fact it seemed to go by faster than I thought it would. I enjoyed the different images.

Strategy Description: I looked at the list from a holistic perspective at first as some of the trials were much easier to immediately understand than others.   Once I reviewed holistically, I then looked at individual terms to determine if they were all generally applicable to the A Group or if there were some outliers that did not fit in with the A Group.  At that point, based first on the holistic perspective and then the indivivdual perspective, I then made my decision.
EasyHardTrials: There were a couple of the bathroom trials where I did feel as if I was splitting hairs in deciding between the two groups.   Some of the other trials were particularly easy when there was absolutely no crossover between the words in the two groups.
Fatigue: I didn't start to get tired.  However, I recognized some of the pictures from previous trials so I required less time as I had already analyzed which pictures were included in that group.
MoreTrials: I could probably have done another 100 trials and still maintained my attention span and focus.
